  "prompt_text": "Design a rate limiter for an API. What data structures and algorithms would you use?",
  "response_text": "To design a rate limiter for an API, we need to ensure that the API can handle requests within certain limits to prevent abuse or overloading. Here are the key components and data structures/algorithms that can be used:\n\n### Key Components\n\n1. **User Identification**: Each request must be associated with a user or a client identifier.\n2. **Rate Limits**: Define the maximum number of requests allowed per time window (e.g., per minute, per hour).\n3. **Time Windows**: Define the duration of the time window (e.g., 1 minute, 5 minutes).\n\n### Data Structures and Algorithms\n\n#### 1. Token Bucket Algorithm\nThe Token Bucket algorithm is a simple and effective way to implement rate limiting. It works as follows:\n- **Token Bucket**: A bucket that holds tokens. Each token represents one request.\n- **Refill Rate**: Tokens are added to the bucket at a constant rate.\n- **Request Rate**: When a request comes in, it checks if there is a token available in the bucket. If so, the token is removed, and the request is processed. Otherwise, the request is rejected.\n\n**Data Structure**: \n- A queue to hold tokens.\n- A timer to refill the bucket at a constant rate.\n\n**Algorithm**:\n- Initialize the bucket with a certain number of tokens.\n- At each time interval, add new tokens to the bucket.\n- When a request comes in, check if there is a token available. If yes, process the request and remove the token from the bucket. If no, reject the request.\n\n#### 2. Leaky Bucket Algorithm\nThe Leaky Bucket algorithm is another approach to rate limiting. It works as follows:\n- **Bucket**: A bucket that holds requests.\n- **Leak Rate**: Requests are removed from the bucket at a constant rate.\n- **Request Rate**: When a request comes in, it is added to the bucket. If the bucket is full, the request is dropped.\n\n**Data Structure**:\n- A queue to hold requests.\n- A timer to remove requests from the bucket at a constant rate.\n\n**Algorithm**:\n- Initialize the bucket with a certain capacity.\n- At each time interval, remove requests from the bucket.\n- When a request comes in, add it to the bucket. If the bucket is full, drop the request.\n\n#### 3. Sliding Window Algorithm\nThe Sliding Window algorithm is useful when you want to enforce rate limits based on recent activity. It works as follows:\n- **Window**: A fixed-size window of time.\n- **Counters**: Counters to keep track of the number of requests in the current window.\n\n**Data Structure**:\n- A list or array to store counters for each time slot in the window.\n- A timer to update the counters as the window slides.\n\n**Algorithm**:\n- Divide the time window into smaller slots (e.g., every second).\n- Maintain a counter for each slot.\n-",
